******
[1] Negros Occidental province
Date: Sat 20 Jul 2013
Source: The Visayan Daily Star [edited]
http://www.visayandailystar.com/2013/July/20/topstory5.htm


In Negros Occidental, 56 cases of chikungunya fever, which is often accompanied by very debilitating joint pains, have been reported, 50 of which were in Kabankalan City and 6 in Cadiz City, the Provincial Health Office reported yesterday [19 Jul 2013].

Chikungunya fever is a viral illness transmitted through the bite of infected _Aedes_ mosquitoes, the same carrier of dengue fever, Dr. Ernell Tumimbang, Negros Occidental provincial health officer, said.

The illness resembles dengue fever as it usually co-occurs and is often misdiagnosed.

The symptoms of chikungunya fever include sudden onset of fever, severe headache, chills, nausea, vomiting, accompanied by severe and sometimes persistent joint pains, but it is generally not fatal unlike dengue, Tumimbang said.

Of the 50 cases of Chikungunya in Kabankalan City, 44 were in Barangay Magballo, 4 in Barangay Bantayan, and one each in barangays Locotan and Balicotoc.

In Cadiz City, the 6 cases reported were in Barangay Jerusalem.

Some chikungunya patients have reported incapacitating joint pains, or arthritis, that may last for weeks or months. The areas around the joints become swollen and painful to touch, a Center for Health Development - Western Visayas advisory said.

Such prolonged joint pain and fatigue associated with chikungunya fever are not typical of dengue. A rash may sometimes occur but hemorrhaging is rare, it added.

Time from the infected bite to the onset of illness can be 2 to 12 days, but usually it is 3 to 7 days, the advisory said.

If you have chikungunya fever symptoms, see a doctor, it advised.

Currently, there is no specific drug treatment against chikungunya fever but proper and early treatment with bed rest and sufficient intake of fluids is recommended, the advisory said. Aspirin and ibuprofen should be avoided as they are known to increase the risk of bleeding, while paracetamol can be given on medical advice, the advisory added.

To avoid mosquito bites, one should wear full-sleeve clothes and long dresses to cover the limbs, and use repellants, but care should be taken in using them on small children and the elderly, it added.

It also advised the use of mosquito nets to protect babies and old people, who may rest during the day.

Mosquito nets and coils will effectively prevent mosquitoes from biting sick people and help stop the spread of chikungunya fever [virus], the advisory also said.

Tumimbang reiterated the call for the public to remove possible mosquito breeding places such as containers with stagnant water to prevent the spread of dengue and Chikungunya.

[Byline: Carla Gomez]

